            <fr:route>/0080/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Diversity is All You Need">Diversity is All You Need</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>The talk starts discussing <fr:link href="/beneysenbach/" title="Benjamin Eysenbach" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/beneysenbach/" display-uri="beneysenbach" type="local">Ben's</fr:link> amazing paper <fr:link href="/eysenbachDiversityAllYou2018/" title="Diversity is All You Need: Learning Skills without a Reward Function" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/eysenbachDiversityAllYou2018/" display-uri="eysenbachDiversityAllYou2018" type="local">DIAYN</fr:link>. An idea that has become incredibly popular in unsupervised / self-supervised RL is learning <html:em>conditional</html:em> policies. In <fr:link href="/0005/" title="All things contrastive reinforcement learning" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/0005/" display-uri="0005" type="local">All things contrastive reinforcement learning</fr:link>, the learn a <html:em>goal-conditioned</html:em> policy and value function i.e.
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\pi _{\theta }(s \mid  g), \quad  Q_{\psi }(s, a, g)]]></fr:tex>
However, we are not limited to goals. In <fr:link href="/machadoTemporalAbstractionReinforcement2023/" title="Temporal Abstraction in Reinforcement Learning with the Successor Representation" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/machadoTemporalAbstractionReinforcement2023/" display-uri="machadoTemporalAbstractionReinforcement2023" type="local">successor-feature-based</fr:link> frameworks, one learns a <html:em>task</html:em> vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {w}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[r(s, a) = \phi (s,a) \cdot  \mathbf {w},]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi ]]></fr:tex> is a lower dimensional representation. To learn the task vector (assuming you have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi ]]></fr:tex> which is a whole other issue), you can recover <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {w}]]></fr:tex> by solving the linear regression
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\min _{\psi } \|r(s,a) - \phi (s,a) \cdot  \mathbf {w}_{\psi }\|^{2} ]]></fr:tex>
One can then learn a <html:em>task</html:em> conditioned policy <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _{\theta }(s \mid  \mathbf {w})]]></fr:tex>. This is precisely the idea in USFA.
</html:p><html:p>Getting back to <fr:link href="/eysenbachDiversityAllYou2018/" title="Diversity is All You Need: Learning Skills without a Reward Function" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/eysenbachDiversityAllYou2018/" display-uri="eysenbachDiversityAllYou2018" type="local">DIAYN</fr:link> (get used to these tangents), instead of a <html:em>task</html:em> or <html:em>goal</html:em>, they condition on a <html:em>skill</html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {z}]]></fr:tex>. However, unlike a goal which is just a state in the environment, or a task which can be learned via regression as above, it is unclear how to learn this "skill" <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {z}]]></fr:tex>.
 </html:p><html:p>
  In this paper, they consider a skill as something distinguishable by a third party. What does this mean:
</html:p>
 <html:div class="jms-callout" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.7);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.05);
  "><html:span style="font-weight: 600; color: rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.7);">Remark.</html:span> 
  <html:em>If you have a skill, then a discriminator observing you perform your skill should be able to tell you which skill you performed.</html:em>
  </html:div>
<html:p>
  Crucially, the discriminator does <html:strong>not</html:strong> know which actions you took when performing this skill. Namely, they must be able to identify the skill purely based on the <html:strong>states</html:strong> you visited when performing that skill. Mathematically, this can be roughly translated as maximizing the <fr:link href="/000V/" title="Mutual Information" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/000V/" display-uri="000V" type="local">mutual information</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I^{\pi }(\mathbf {z}; \tau )]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\tau ]]></fr:tex> is a trajectory of states <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(s_0, s_1, \ldots , s_T) \sim  \pi ]]></fr:tex> visited by your policy <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi ]]></fr:tex>. Using our previous knowledge of <fr:link href="/000V/" title="Mutual Information" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/000V/" display-uri="000V" type="local">mutual information</fr:link>, we can rewrite this as
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[I^{\pi }(\mathbf {z}, \tau ) = H(\mathbf {z}) - H(\mathbf {z} \mid  \tau ),]]></fr:tex>
  where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link href="/0081/" title="Entropy" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/0081/" display-uri="0081" type="local">entropy</fr:link>. Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H(\mathbf {z})]]></fr:tex> is a constant, this is essentially,
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\min _{\mathbf {z}} H(\mathbf {z} \mid  \tau )]]></fr:tex>
  which very intuitively corresponds to the notion that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {z}]]></fr:tex> should be able to be <html:em>predicted</html:em> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\tau ]]></fr:tex>. Formally, this is captured by the fact that the <fr:link href="/0081/" title="Entropy" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/0081/" display-uri="0081" type="local">entropy</fr:link> is minimized i.e. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0]]></fr:tex> when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {z} = f(\tau )]]></fr:tex> for some invertible <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>.
  
 <html:div class="jms-callout" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.7);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.05);
  "><html:span style="font-weight: 600; color: rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.7);">Remark.</html:span> 
  Recall that <fr:link href="/0081/" title="Entropy" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/0081/" display-uri="0081" type="local">entropy</fr:link> is actually defined on the PDF of a random variable <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Therefore, minimizing the entropy over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {z}]]></fr:tex> is actually finding a distribution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(\mathbf {z})]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:div>

  To learn the distribution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(\mathbf {z})]]></fr:tex>, they utilize the <fr:link href="/0082/" title="Evidence Lower Bound" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/0082/" display-uri="0082" type="local">ELBO</fr:link>.
  </html:p></fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
